1. When might you want to try GAM?

1.1 The goal

Lets say you are interested in evaluating the relationship between iris sepal width and iris sepal length - maybe you start with a linear model.

library(datasets) #lets use iris
plot(iris$Sepal.Width, iris$Sepal.Length)

The relationship doesnt look that linear, but lets try it anyway and look at the residual vs.fitted plot

iris_lm <- lm(Sepal.Length ~ Sepal.Width, data = iris)

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(iris_lm)

YIKES! The data are normally distributed, but there are some problems with the assumption of linearity between Y and X.

1.2 What can you do about it?

  • Add interaction terms
  • Add more explanatory variables
  • Expand the model by adding a non-linear main effect (like \(x^{2}\))
  • You could transform the variables to linearize the relationship (either response or explanatory). However, transformation affects the entire Y-X relationship, whereas maybe the relationship is partly linear and also partly non-linear along the X gradient

What if you have exhausted these options and dont want to transform? One option is to use smoothing models or GAM

2.1 Things to keep in mind when fitting GAMs

  • We want an arbitrary smooth curve to relate Y to X
  • We can construct such a curve by adding together many simpler curves
  • To control for the underfitting-overfitting tradeoff, we allow the smoother to have a large number of components (i.e., many curves or splines), but we control for the wiggliness of the curve using a penalty term \(\lambda\)
  • The optimal penalty term is chosen as part of the fitting process via generalized cross-validation

3.1 Fitting GAMs with mgcv

  • the choice for running GAMs in R
  • There are as many smoothing techniques as there are roads to Rome - Zurr 2009
  • mgcv estimates smoothers using thin plate regression splines (default)
library(mgcv)

3.2 Basic Syntax

Fitting a GAM is similar to fitting a GLM but use s(x) instead of x - This syntax tells the function to fit a smoother to the predictor Sepal.Width

iris_gam <- gam(Sepal.Length ~ s(Sepal.Width), data = iris)
plot(iris_gam)

3.3 Model Summary

  • Default family is gaussian (but it can be specified with an argument family (e.g., family = poisson()). Check out family.mcgv for a full list of whats available in this package

The output has two sections:

  1. List of estimates for any parametric (i.e., not smoothed) predictors. These can be continuous predictors that are not smoothed or factors (e.g., Species)

  2. List of smoothed terms - in this case s(Sepal.Width)

  • The edf is the estimated degrees of freedom and basically is using the wiggliness of the smoother to say if this smoother were written as a parametric equation, this is approximately how many parameters that equation would. Or the number of splines. Shown in y-axis label.
  • F-statistic comes from the approximate F-test for how well variation in Y is explained by the smoother. In this case, significant variation is explained by the smoother
  • Deviance explained is measure of how well the curve explains the data, its equivalent to the unadjusted \(R^{2}\) but for non-Gaussian families, this metric is preffered over \(R^{2}\)
  • GCV,or generalized cross validation score, can be taken as an estimate of the mean square prediction error based on a leave-one-out cross validation estimation process. A lower score is better because it means less predictive error.
summary(iris_gam)
## 
## Family: gaussian 
## Link function: identity 
## 
## Formula:
## Sepal.Length ~ s(Sepal.Width)
## 
## Parametric coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  5.84333    0.06524   89.56   <2e-16 ***
## ---

## GCV = 0.65866  Scale est. = 0.6385    n = 150

3.4 Plotting smoother with partial residuals

  • Partial residuals are the calculated for each observation as the predicted value from the smoother function plus the residual
  • Useful for asking What is the efect of predictor X while accounting for any variation explained by the other predictors in the model?
  • As a final step for plotting, if we want the fitted relationship on the scale of the raw data, we can add the intercept back to the plot (second panel)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(iris_gam, residuals = TRUE, pch = 21)
plot(iris_gam, residuals = TRUE, pch = 21, shift = coef(iris_gam)[1])

3.5 Using gam.check() for residual diagnostics

  • Plots in the left column give a sense for whether the deviance residuals are normally distributed
  • Plots on the right give a sense for whether the variance is homoscedastic (homogeneity of variance)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
gam.check(iris_gam)

## 
## Method: GCV   Optimizer: magic

3.6 You can also use DHARMa

  • Simulation-based approach to create easily interpretable scaled (quantile) residuals for many types of models. It is compatible with GAM models constructed with mgcv
#load package
library(DHARMa)

3.6.1 Run simulation

  • No problems detected here
  • Check it out here: DHARMa Workflow
simulationOutput <- simulateResiduals(fittedModel = iris_gam, plot = T)

4.1 Customize the model

  • gam default settings usually work fairly well
  • We have let the function automate everything involved in fitting the smoother
  • automatically decides how many knots in the spline
  • choses optimal penalty for wiggliness using GCV
    • Too smooth: might miss patterns in the data
    • Too wiggly: might fit subtle or random patterns that reduce predictive performance
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
gam.check(iris_gam)

## 
## Method: GCV   Optimizer: magic
## Smoothing parameter selection converged after 4 iterations.
## The RMS GCV score gradient at convergence was 9.424113e-08 .
## The Hessian was positive definite.
## Model rank =  10 / 10 
## 
## Basis dimension (k) checking results. Low p-value (k-index<1) may
## indicate that k is too low, especially if edf is close to k'.
## 
##                  k'  edf k-index p-value    
## s(Sepal.Width) 9.00 3.59    0.64  <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

4.2 Modifying smoother complexity

  • Output: k is the upper bound on the complexity/wiggliness of the smoother (~ number of knots). During the model optimization process,the function automatically decides the maximum complexity (k) and then it choses the optiaml penalty for wiggliness (\(\lambda\)) using the GCV. This results in the optimized number of spines and is shown as the estimated degrees of freedom (edf). Here it was reduced to 3.59 (less complex smoother).

  • If k is close to the edf then maybe the function did not permit enough complexity to begin with, so we can set k ourselves

iris_gam_k18 <- gam(Sepal.Length ~ s(Sepal.Width, k = 18), data = iris)

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(iris_gam_k18)
plot(iris_gam)

The results look very smiliar which is good! That means that the default settings allowed for enough complexity according to the cross-validation criterion (see the similar edf values on the y-axis). This means that, through the cross-validation process, the wiggliness was penalized to a similar degree and resulted in the same number of splines.

What if the smoother was not penalized for wiggliness? - we can force this to be the case by setting fx = TRUE

iris_gam_k18_fxT <- gam(Sepal.Length ~ s(Sepal.Width, k = 18, fx = TRUE), data = iris)

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(iris_gam_k18)
plot(iris_gam_k18_fxT)

4.3 Compare model summaries

  • iris_gam has the optimal number of splines to have the lowest GCV score
  • GCV score for iris_gam_k18_fxT is higher
  • this curve over-fits the data

5.1 Interaction between a smoother and a factor

  • We can also compare the smooth curves among groups (i.e., a factor - in this case Species)
  • Useful for answering the question Does the relationship between Y and X differ between or among groups?
  • use the by argument in the s() function which fits a smoother curve to each species
  • Note: we also need to include the parametric term for Species so that way the smoothers will quantify whether species differ in the shape of the smoother curve after any difference in mean sepal width among species has already been accounted for
iris_gam2 <- gam(Sepal.Length ~ Species + s(Sepal.Width, by = Species), data = iris)
summary(iris_gam2)
##

## Link function: identity

All of the smoothers are significant, lets see what they look like among species:

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(iris_gam2)

Next we want to know whether a given species differs from the overall relationship fit by the first smoother s(Sepal.Width). The code below will also give a set of plots that show us if the smoother fit for virginica differs from the overall relationship fit by the first smoother. This is useful if you want to quantify how smoothers differ among groups

iris_gam3 <- gam(Sepal.Length ~ Species + s(Sepal.Width) + s(Sepal.Width, by = as.numeric(Species == "virginica")), data = iris)
summary(iris_gam3)

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(iris_gam3)

  1. The first graph shows the smoother for Sepal.width after we account for species (which becomes linear, see the edf on the y-axis, which is 1).
  2. The second graph shows us how the smoother for virginica differs from the overall smoother. Values on the y-axis indicate how different is from the overall relationship. Values of 0 indicate no difference. You can see that the relationship between Sepal.width and Sepal.length in Iris virginica deviate from the overall relationship most at large values of Sepal.Width; however, differences between virginica and the overall relationship across the range of Sepal.width include 0 in the standard error. This indicates that smoother for virginica is not significantly different from the overall smoother (after accounting for variation due to Species)

6.1 Comparing models with AIC(c)

GAM models can be compared using AIC just like GLMs

AIC(iris_gam) #just one predictor s(Sepal.width)
## [1] 364.9064
AIC(iris_gam2) #includes species as a parametric variable (Species) and smooth variable (s(Sepal.))
## [1] 184.3487
